#### Feature Description

Drag preview DOM insertion location is currently the document body or fullscreen element.

```ts
/** Gets the element into which the drag preview should be inserted. */
function getPreviewInsertionPoint(documentRef: any): HTMLElement {
  // We can't use the body if the user is in fullscreen mode,
  // because the preview will render under the fullscreen element.
  // TODO(crisbeto): dedupe this with the `FullscreenOverlayContainer` eventually.
  return documentRef.fullscreenElement ||
         documentRef.webkitFullscreenElement ||
         documentRef.mozFullScreenElement ||
         documentRef.msFullscreenElement ||
         documentRef.body;
}
```

...which is being used here:
```ts
  /** Starts the dragging sequence. */
  private _startDragSequence(event: MouseEvent | TouchEvent) {
    // ...
    const dropContainer = this._dropContainer;

    if (dropContainer) {
      // ...
      const preview = this._preview = this._createPreviewElement();
      // ...
      getPreviewInsertionPoint(this._document).appendChild(preview);
      // ...
    } else {
      // ...
    }
  // ...
  }
```

It would be nice to have an `@Input() previewInsertionPoint: ElementRef | HTMLElement` for the `CdkDropList` directive to specify a custom location, other than the document body, to append the preview element.

The above code would then change to something like:
```ts
  /** Starts the dragging sequence. */
  private _startDragSequence(event: MouseEvent | TouchEvent) {
    // ...
    const dropContainer = this._dropContainer;

    if (dropContainer) {
      // ...
      const preview = this._preview = this._createPreviewElement();
      // getPreviewInsertionPoint(this._document).appendChild(preview);
      const previewInsertionPoint = dropContainer.previewInsertionPoint ? coerceElement(dropContainer.previewInsertionPoint) : getPreviewInsertionPoint(this._document);
      previewInsertionPoint.appendChild(preview);
      // ...
    } else {
      // ...
    }
  // ...
  }
```

#### Use Case

A custom preview insertion location will allow for more advanced stacking/ordering layouts and styling. I have a specific use case with a drop list + boundary element, where I **always** want the drag items to be rendered under certain surrounding elements. When the drop list is sitting statically, it looks fine. But when I start dragging, the preview is rendered above everything else - which is okay for a lot of drag and drop scenarios but not mine.

Consider drop shadow CSS styling. The drop shadow can visually extend beyond the drag boundary, while the element itself is still contained inside the drag boundary. As stated above, when the list and drag items are sitting statically, the drop shadow extending beyond the drag boundary is being hidden by the ordering/z-index/styling of other elements (which is what I want). The moment the preview element (w/ drop shadow applied) becomes active, it's drop shadow is completely visible and extending outside of the drag boundary and there is nothing I can do about it because the preview element is in a completely different DOM location (bottom of document body, on top of everything) nowhere near the drop list and it's neighboring elements.

Let me know if you need anymore info.

Also, a public `dragRef.getPlaceholderElement()` method exists. Can a public `dragRef.getPreviewElement()` method also be added to allow accessing the preview element during hooks/events?

Testing values being set into an autocomplete is difficult due to opaque change detection requirements. The `setValue` function in the autocomplete uses a Promise to wait to set the value, and then change detection must be run afterwards to float the label. This is an issue we see internally at Google where screenshot diffs are off because clients don't understand the complex set of change detection and promises they are required to run.

To observe, insert and test the following in `autocomplete.spec.ts`:

```

  it('should have reasonable expectations for setting the value and float the label', async () => {
    const fixture = createComponent(AutocompleteWithLabel);
    fixture.componentInstance.myFormControl.setValue('testValue');
    fixture.detectChanges();

    const input = fixture.nativeElement.querySelector('input');
    const formField = fixture.nativeElement.querySelector('mat-form-field') as HTMLElement;
    
    // At this point, the form field's value has been been set, and we should expect that the
    // input contains the right value and the label is floating. This is not true because
    // the autocomplete's trigger waits for a promise to be resolved in `setValue` to actually
    // set the value
    expect(input.value).toBe('testValue');  // Fails
    expect(formField.classList.contains('mat-form-field-should-float')).toBe(true);  // Fails

    // Wait for a timeout and test again. Now we see that the value has been set, but the form
    // field still does not have a floating label because change detection has not run again to
    // find that the value is present.
    await new Promise(resolve => setTimeout(resolve, 0));
    expect(input.value).toBe('testValue');  // Succeeds
    expect(formField.classList.contains('mat-form-field-should-float')).toBe(true);  // Fails

    // Finally, detect changes again to see that the label floats.
    fixture.detectChanges();
    expect(input.value).toBe('testValue');  // Succeeds
    expect(formField.classList.contains('mat-form-field-should-float')).toBe(true);  // Succeeds
  });


@Component({
  template: `
    <mat-form-field appearance="outline">
      <mat-label>
        My label
      </mat-label>
      <input matInput
             [formControl]="myFormControl"
             [matAutocomplete]="auto">
      <mat-autocomplete #auto="matAutocomplete">
      </mat-autocomplete>
    </mat-form-field>
  `
})
class AutocompleteWithLabel {
  myFormControl = new FormControl();
}

```
